        </list>
        <div id="nonsensical-notes" type="gl-notes">
            <head>Notes</head>
            <list type="simple">
                <item><name>Gabriel Bodard</name> (<date>2008-04-24</date>): it has been decided to
                    deprecate the use of <att>n</att> on this element, so that <tag>orig</tag>
                    without parent::<tag>choice</tag> means an unresolved character, as opposed to
                    <tag>orig</tag> (parallel to <tag>reg</tag>) inside of <tag>choice</tag>
                    which is a local or irregular form requiring normalization. <note>GB: As of this change we
                    no longer have a way to indicate the specific cases of u/v whose vocality is unresolved, or σ/ς whose
                    context (medial/final) is unresolved. Is this a problem?</note></item>
                <item>The general case of unresolved characters is handled by the use of the
                        <tag>orig</tag> element with the <att>n</att> attribute containing
                    "unresolved". For more particular cases, such as the Latin <foreign lang="la"
                    >V</foreign> identified by Dohnicht as ambiguously vocalic or consonantal, the
                    attribute may be further specified with the addition of "_vocality", <foreign
                        lang="la">vel sim.</foreign></item>
            </list>
        </div>
    </div>

